{
  "doc_id": "22808",
  "text": "Additional HPV proteins are required to maintain an environment conducive to viral replication. The oncogenic HPV E6 and E7 proteins promote cellular proliferation, delay cellular differentiation, and promote immune evasion (reviewed in [CITATION_1] ). Both E6 and E7 are required for productive replication [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] and it was long thought that E6 and E7 were required to sustain differentiated cells in a pseudo-S phase to provide access to host DNA replication machinery. However, in a stratified epithelium, the differentiated cells that amplify viral genomes are in a G2 like phase that is also dependent on E7 expression [CITATION_5] 17] . As described below, E6 and E7 play essential roles in modulating the cellular DDR for viral replication.",
